<Base title="Killing the 60-second timeout — Andrew Yang">
  <p><a href={`${base}/work/`}>← Case studies</a></p>
  <span class="tag">async design</span>
  <h1>Killing the 60-second timeout: queue-ifying a million-datapoint export</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Some requests cannot be made fast enough — they have to stop being requests.
    Redesigning a synchronous CSV export into a queue-backed job system, with the
    design documents to match.
  </p>

  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>
    The monitoring platform lets customers export measurement data as CSV. The
    original implementation was fully synchronous: HTTP request in, CSV out, with
    the web server enforcing a 60-second timeout on everything.
  </p>

  <h2>Problem</h2>
  <p>
    A customer with a ~300-plant portfolio requested an export of roughly
    <strong>820,000 datapoints</strong> — reproducibly dead at the 60-second
    wall, and no amount of query tuning was going to buy a 10× margin. The
    system also had an explicit ceiling of one million datapoints per export
    hardcoded in three places, so "just make it faster" had already been tried
    by history.
  </p>

  <h2>Design</h2>
  <p>The fix is architectural: turn the request into a job.</p>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      <strong>Dedup by construction:</strong> a job table keyed by a
      <strong>hash of the export parameters</strong>, with find-or-create
      semantics — two users (or one impatient user double-clicking) requesting
      the same export share one job instead of running the heavy query twice.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A queue-backed worker:</strong> export jobs go onto a message
      queue; a worker generates the CSV off the request path and writes it to
      object storage. The web request returns immediately with the job handle.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Completion push, not polling:</strong> the requesting user gets a
      per-user push notification when the file is ready to download.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Lifecycle hygiene:</strong> a state machine for the job
      (requested → processing → done/failed), a cleanup cron that expires
      generated files after three days, and the datapoint ceiling enforced in
      one place instead of three.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The deliverable included the full design documentation — sequence diagram,
    job state machine, API contract, and the dedup table DDL — so the design was
    reviewable before the first line of implementation.
  </p>

  <h2>Impact</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      The timeout failure mode is eliminated <em>by construction</em> — export
      duration and HTTP timeouts are no longer coupled at all.
    </li>
    <li>
      Duplicate heavy exports collapse into one job; the expensive path is
      protected from accidental self-DoS.
    </li>
    <li>
      The pattern generalizes: any "generate something big on demand" feature on
      the platform now has a reference architecture to copy.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What I'd tell my past self</h2>
  <p>
    The interesting decision wasn't the queue — it was recognizing that a
    latency problem was actually a <em>product-shape</em> problem. Once the
    export became a job with an identity (the parameter hash), everything else —
    dedup, retries, notification, cleanup — followed from ordinary engineering.
    I run the same playbook in my <a href={`${base}/demo/`}>ai-radar demo</a>,
    where the budget circuit breaker parks work in the queue for the next
    window: queues are for decoupling "accepted" from "done".
  </p>
</Base>
